@NODE requirements "Requirements"
@NEXT usage
@PREV copyright

   - an  Amiga
   - OS  3+
   - MUI 3+
   - Screen min. 640 x 256 for topaz/8
   - min. 8 colours (MWB) or better 18 free pens for full colors
   - min. 1.5 MB free memory

@ENDNODE

@NODE usage "Usage"
@NEXT tooltypes
@PREV requirements
   @{fg fill}
   This program performs only read operations on the devices so that
   nothing will be destroyed!!
   @{fg shadow}
   You can start the program from CLI or Workbench. In both cases the
   @{"tooltypes" link tooltypes} will be evaluated.
   After the start a small window appears and visualizes the start
   procedure. Then the main window will be opened.

   Here you can select devices, set the buffersize and choose a testmode.
   You can also call the @{b}Information Window@{ub} from menu to change
   the most settings. The changes are only available in the current
   session and will not be saved yet.

   @{fg shine}@{b}@{u}Select Devices@{uu}@{ub}@{fg shadow}

      To select doubleclick the entry. If an entry is selected a little
      colourfield appears in the left column. This field shows the
      colour of the related bar in the display.
      It's possible to add or remove devices to/from a running test.
      If you remove the last one the test will be stopped.


   @{fg shine}@{b}@{u}Buffersize@{uu}@{ub}@{fg shadow}

      This cycle gadget contains values from 512 byte to 512 kbyte.
      It's possible to change it while the test is running.
      Set the memory type by using the @{b}Information Window@{ub} from menu
      or use the @{"tooltypes" link tooltypes}.
      @{fg fill}@{i}
      Be sure that your host adapter can handle the selected size!
      Check also the max. transfer rate for the device.
      @{ui}@{fg shadow}


   @{fg shine}@{b}@{u}Testmode@{uu}@{ub}@{fg shadow}

      You can choose between 3 modes:

       @{i}Same Sector:@{ui}
         Reads permanently a block of the size of the selected buffersize
         from block 0 into memory.

       @{i}Sequential:@{ui}
         Reads the blocks sequentially, starting from block 0, into
         memory. After reading the last block reading starts again
         from 0.

       @{i}Random:@{ui}
         Reads permanently one buffer from a random selected block into
         memory.

@ENDNODE

@NODE tooltypes "Tooltypes"
@NEXT history
@PREV usage

   @{fg shine}@{b}USE_HD_SCSICMD@{ub}@{fg shadow}

      If it's @{b}ON@{ub} SCSI direct commands will be used instead of
      device commands.
      You can also set this by using the @{b}Information Window@{ub} from menu.

      @{i}Default is OFF.@{ui}


   @{fg shine}@{b}SHOW_SIZE_ALLERT@{ub}@{fg shadow}

      If it's @{b}ON@{ub} the warning window for big read buffers will
      be shown when you select a buffer greater 64K.
      This is necessary to avoid crashes if your host adapter can't
      handle this.
      You can also set this by using the @{b}Information Window@{ub} from menu.

      @{i}Default is ON.@{ui}


   @{fg shine}@{b}USE_INTERNAL_DEVICE_LIST@{ub}@{fg shadow}

      Allows you to switch off the internal device list.
      This list contains devices and max unit numbers which work well
      with the automatically device check.
      Is your device not included and it works with the SCSI_DEVICE
      tooltype send us a short note:
         @{b}
         Host Adapter Name(s),
         Devicename(s) used by this host adapter,
         Max Unit Number
         @{ub}
      @{i}Default is ON.@{ui}


   @{fg shine}@{b}DEVICE@{ub}@{fg shadow}

      Here you can add your own device(s) and max. unit number(s).
      If your device is included in the internal list there is no
      need to use this tooltype. But it's possible to overload the
      max. unit number of a list entry when you have problems or
      you want to extend the range.
      The internal list can be found in the @{b}Information Window@{ub}.

      DEVICE=<devicename>[,max_unit_number]

      @{i}Default for max_unit_number is 7.@{ui}
      @{fg fill}
      Examples:
      ---------
      DEVICE=MASOBOSHI.device
      DEVICE=fastscsi.device,11
      @{fg shadow}

   @{fg shine}@{b}IDLE@{ub}@{fg shadow}

      Sets the type of the CPU usage display.
      The following values are available:

         @{fg fill}@{i}OFF @{ui}@{fg shadow}         : Switches the display off.
         @{fg fill}@{i}STANDARD @{ui}@{fg shadow}    : Uses a subtask system to get percentage.
                        @{i}This method affects the results!!@{ui}
         @{fg fill}@{i}SYSTEM @{ui}@{fg shadow}      : Not implemented yet!
         @{fg fill}@{i}EXECUTIVE @{ui}@{fg shadow}   : Uses the Executive-System to calculatate percentage.

      You can also set this by using the @{b}Information Window@{ub} from menu.

      @{i}Default is STANDARD.@{ui}


   @{fg shine}@{b}UPDATE_TIME@{ub}@{fg shadow}

      Sets the time for the display update.
      The valid range is from 2 to 30 seconds.

      @{i}Default is 2 sec.@{ui}


   @{fg shine}@{b}BUFFER_TYPE@{ub}@{fg shadow}

      This tooltype sets the memory type of the used test buffer.
      You can choose between @{b}CHIP@{ub} and @{b}FAST@{ub}.
      You can also set this by using the @{b}Information Window@{ub} from menu.

      @{i}Default is FAST.@{ui}


   @{fg shine}@{b}LANGUAGE@{ub}@{fg shadow}

      Use this tooltype to set the language for the catalog file.

      @{i}Build-in language is english.@{ui}


@ENDNODE

